Compute Simple Effect Sizes

Martin Zettersten

2022-06-08

Read Data

Simple computation of effect sizes from example power analysis datasets

dataset_1 <- read_csv(here::here("power_analysis","simulated_data","example_power_analysis_data_0.3.csv"))
## Rows: 30720 Columns: 11
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (1): stimulus_type
## dbl (10): fam_time, dv_zscore, subjID, labID, age, age_mos, subjInt, labInt,...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Plot Main Effects

Familiarization

#summarize by subject
d_sub_fam <- dataset_1 %>%
  group_by(subjID,fam_time) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_looking = mean(dv_zscore,na.rm=TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subjID'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(d_sub_fam,aes(as.factor(fam_time),mean_looking))+
  geom_violin()+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.1)

Stimulus Type

#summarize by subject
d_sub_stim_type <- dataset_1 %>%
  group_by(subjID,stimulus_type) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_looking = mean(dv_zscore,na.rm=TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subjID'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(d_sub_stim_type,aes(as.factor(stimulus_type),mean_looking))+
  geom_violin()+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.1)

Age

#summarize by subject
d_sub_age <- dataset_1 %>%
  group_by(subjID,age) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_looking = mean(dv_zscore,na.rm=TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subjID'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(d_sub_age,aes(age,mean_looking))+
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.1)+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Effect sizes

All together

m <- lmer(dv_zscore ~ fam_time*stimulus_type*age+(1|subjID)+(1|labID), data = dataset_1)
anova(m)
## Type III Analysis of Variance Table with Satterthwaite's method
##                             Sum Sq Mean Sq NumDF   DenDF   F value    Pr(>F)
## fam_time                   1301.16 1301.16     1 29434.0 1706.0942 < 2.2e-16
## stimulus_type               513.08  513.08     1 29434.0  672.7577 < 2.2e-16
## age                          79.42   79.42     1  1240.7  104.1387 < 2.2e-16
## fam_time:stimulus_type       32.40   32.40     1 29434.0   42.4792 7.259e-11
## fam_time:age                 10.46   10.46     1 29434.0   13.7150 0.0002131
## stimulus_type:age             0.79    0.79     1 29434.0    1.0398 0.3078777
## fam_time:stimulus_type:age    0.87    0.87     1 29434.0    1.1455 0.2845030
##                               
## fam_time                   ***
## stimulus_type              ***
## age                        ***
## fam_time:stimulus_type     ***
## fam_time:age               ***
## stimulus_type:age             
## fam_time:stimulus_type:age    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#fam_time effect size
F_to_d(anova(m)[1,5],anova(m)[1,3],anova(m)[1,4])
## d    |       95% CI
## -------------------
## 0.48 | [0.36, 0.50]
#stimulus type effect size
F_to_d(anova(m)[2,5],anova(m)[2,3],anova(m)[2,4])
## d    |       95% CI
## -------------------
## 0.30 | [0.28, 0.33]
#age effect size
F_to_d(anova(m)[3,5],anova(m)[3,3],anova(m)[3,4])
## d    |       95% CI
## -------------------
## 0.58 | [0.47, 0.69]

Familiarization Alone

Familiarization Time

LMER

m <- lmer(dv_zscore ~ fam_time+(1|subjID)+(1|labID), data = dataset_1)
anova(m)
## Type III Analysis of Variance Table with Satterthwaite's method
##          Sum Sq Mean Sq NumDF DenDF F value    Pr(>F)    
## fam_time 1301.2  1301.2     1 29439    1665 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
F_to_d(anova(m)[1,5],anova(m)[1,3],anova(m)[1,4])
## d    |       95% CI
## -------------------
## 0.48 | [0.40, 0.50]
#model comparison
# marginal R squared
r.squaredGLMM(m)[1]
## Warning: 'r.squaredGLMM' now calculates a revised statistic. See the help page.
## [1] 0.01767212

Stimulus Type Alone

Subject-level averages

d_sub_stim_type_paired <- d_sub_stim_type %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "stimulus_type",values_from = "mean_looking") %>%
  mutate(
    diff = high - low
  )

#cohens_d(diff ~ 1, data=d_sub_stim_type_paired)
#Cohen's d
mean(d_sub_stim_type_paired$diff)/sd(d_sub_stim_type_paired$diff)
## [1] 0.7272561

LMER

m <- lmer(dv_zscore ~ stimulus_type+(1|subjID)+(1|labID), data = dataset_1)
anova(m)
## Type III Analysis of Variance Table with Satterthwaite's method
##               Sum Sq Mean Sq NumDF DenDF F value    Pr(>F)    
## stimulus_type 513.08  513.08     1 29439  634.82 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
F_to_d(anova(m)[1,5],anova(m)[1,3],anova(m)[1,4])
## d    |       95% CI
## -------------------
## 0.29 | [0.27, 0.32]
# marginal R squared
r.squaredGLMM(m)[1]
## [1] 0.006968367
